<head>
<title>Team Energy--1996 Summer Games in Atlanta</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000080" link="#CD0000" alink="#8B2252" vlink="#004236" >

<a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap.cgi/picts/smeren16.map"><IMG align=right
IMG SRC="/picts/smeren16.gif" alt="[EREN
logo]" ISMAP border=0></a>
<p><strong>U.S. Department of Energy</strong>
<h1 align=left>Olympics</h1>
<strong>Team Energy</strong>
<br clear=all>

<center>
<p><br>
<strong>1996 Summer Games in Atlanta</strong>
</center>

<p>
<img border=0 hspace=20 vspace=8 align=left src="poolpv.gif">
<p><font size=+2>T</font>he U.S. Department of Energy has joined with other public and private 
organizations to form "Team Energy," which is demonstrating energy 
efficiency and renewable energy technologies at the site of the 1996 
Summer Olympic Games in Atlanta.  Demonstrations of commercially-available 
or near-commercial technologies are showing the world that these means of 
saving and producing clean energy are technologies not only for the 
future, but for the present.

<p>Several renewable energy technologies are on display in Atlanta, including 
photovoltaic panels and solar thermal pool heating systems on the roof of 
the Georgia Tech Aquatic Center, a solar thermal dish/Stirling system for 
generating power, and alternative fuel vehicles.  Team Energy also 
constructed the Southface Energy and Environmental Resource Center in 
downtown Atlanta.  The center showcases building energy conservation 
techniques, natural cooling methods, and a geothermal heat pump system 
that provides space heating, cooling, and hot water.

<p><br><br>
<p>
<br clear=all>
<a href="energy.html">
<img border=0 align=left hspace=10 alt="Renewable Energy at the Games"
src="energy_but.gif"></a>
